  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="11" relname="background">Intuitiveness is the most fundamental concept regarding a good user interface. </segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="17" relname="span">
The key point of Intuitiveness is easy to learn, especially for the first-time-user. </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="12" relname="preparation">
In most cases, Intuitiveness affects users from the following two situations: </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="19" relname="span">
1. Users, including those novices, can figure it out how to operate correctly,</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="9" relname="concession"> even though there is only minimal interaction or assistance available from the user documentation. </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="12" relname="list">
2. Users, including those novices, can pick it up quickly and easily whenever there is an unambiguous situation.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="18" relname="span"> 

However, Intuitiveness comes from the users&apos; previous personal experience, knowledge, and skills. </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="15" relname="span">
Intuitiveness cannot be inherited from the Heaven directly. </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="4" relname="condition">
If a user has some word processing experience, </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="span">
he/she will not have much difficulty to figure out how to use different word processing software, 
such as Microsofts Word or Corels WordPerfect, </segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="3" relname="concession">
even though there is no the user documentation or the tutors assistance available.</segment>
